## .NET MAUI Theme Detection & Override

### 1. Detect Current System Theme

```csharp
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified
```

### 2. Subscribe to Theme Changes

```csharp
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");
    // Update UI or trigger re-theming logic here
};
```

### 3. Force a Specific Theme (Override System)

```csharp
// Force dark mode regardless of system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Force light mode
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

### Putting It Together

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        MainPage = new AppShell();

        RequestedThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    private void OnThemeChanged(object sender, AppThemeChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"System theme now: {e.RequestedTheme}");
        // Refresh styles, swap resource dictionaries, etc.
    }

    // Call from a settings page toggle
    public void SetUserThemePreference(AppTheme theme)
    {
        UserAppTheme = theme; // Overrides system; Unspecified = follow system
    }
}
```

### XAML â€” Reactive Theme Resources

You can also bind colors directly to system theme in XAML using `AppThemeBinding`:

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

These bindings update automatically when the theme changes â€” no code-behind needed for simple color swaps.

**Key points:**
- `RequestedTheme` = what the OS reports
- `UserAppTheme` = your app-level override (`Unspecified` means "follow OS")
- `RequestedThemeChanged` fires on OS changes even if `UserAppTheme` overrides rendering
